What are the gender differences in young adults?¶

by Akash Malla, Santa Clara University (Independent Study Project)

This notebook will analyze Young People survey data from Kaggle. The dataset can be found and downloaded from the below URL: https://www.kaggle.com/miroslavsabo/young-people-survey/data

The objective of this notebook is to identify what attributes describe a person to be a man or a women.

#create sub-dataset that will be used for predicting perceived ability to save

interests = data.iloc[:,31:64]

def plotCorrelation(variable, mainDataFrame, map):
    figsize = (10,30)
    def calculateCorrelation(variable, df, cols, figsize):
        labels = []
        values = []
        for c in cols:
            labels.append(c)
            values.append(np.corrcoef(df[c], df[variable])[0,1])
        correlations = pd.DataFrame({'features': labels, 'correlatedValues': values})
        correlations = correlations.sort_values(by = 'correlatedValues')
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize= figsize)
        sns.barplot(x=correlations.correlatedValues, y = correlations['features'],  ax = ax)
        ax.set_title("Correlation coefficient of features based on Gender")
        ax.set_ylabel("Correlation coefficients")
        return correlations
    #Take a copy and update the dataset for Gender column
    df = copy.deepcopy(mainDataFrame)
    df.replace(map, inplace = True)
    
    #correlating integer features
    integerColumns = [c for c in df.columns if df[c].dtype != 'object']
    integerColumns.remove(variable)
    integerCorrelations = calculateCorrelation(variable, df, integerColumns, figsize)
    
    #correlating categorical data
    categoricalColumns = [c for c in df.columns if df[c].dtype == 'object']
    if categoricalColumns:
        dfDummies = pd.get_dummies(df[categoricalColumns])
        categoricalColumns = dfDummies.columns
        dfDummies[variable] = df[variable]
        categoricalCorrelations = calculateCorrelation(variable, dfDummies, categoricalColumns, (5,10))
    else:
        categoricalCorrelations = 0
    return [integerCorrelations, categoricalCorrelations]
    
correlations_area = plotCorrelation('Gender', df3, {'Gender': {'female': 0, 'male': 1}})

The correlation graph suggests women tend to encounter much more life struggles ("I cry when I feel down or things don't go the right way") and feel Romantic (rated high for romantic movies) in contrast to men. Similarly, men have great interest in Cars and PC (PC Software, Hardware).

Weight and Height are obvious differences between men and women which is not surprising.

Interestingly, women in general tend to often run late rather than men are often on time.

Below are my insights that describe features of men:

  1. If you look at the top features that men have, you can conclude if a person loves to be active and likes technology and action movies, then the person is very likely a man.
  2. If you notice, in current IT industry, there is a huge number of gender inequality. There are lot of organizations and even companies that are promoting women to join Tech companies.
  3. Since men love active sports, that can be related to why they love War and Sci-Fi films as they are fast paced action films. This attitude makes sense of why men have rated highly for Cars.

Below are my insights that describe features of women:

  1. Women are tend to be more emotional which is why we can see Life struggles and Psychology is very important and more personal to them.
  2. They are more concerned about their appearance which is why they end up spending more time on their looks, this is related to why they end up shopping and rated high for celebrities.
  3. We can also see that women are mostly light hearted due to their interest in musicals and their compassion to animals and their preference of watching romantic movies.

Interestingly, most men have rated high for being very patient (Waiting) which is great compatibility with women who have rated higher for running late.
